    Davidi Jonas | Straight Path Communications Inc. | ZoomInfo.comStraight Path Communications' (STRP) CEO Davidi Jonas on Q4 2016 Results - Earnings Call Transcript | Seeking AlphaSign in / Join NowGO»Straight Path Communications' (STRP) CEO Davidi Jonas on Q4 2016 Results - Earnings Call TranscriptOct. 7.16 | About: Straight Path (STRP) Straight Path Communications Inc. (NYSEMKT:STRP)
Q4 2016 Earnings Conference Call
October 7, 2016 4:15 PM ET
Executives
Davidi Jonas - President and Chief Executive Officer
Jonathan Rand - Chief Financial Officer and Treasurer
Analysts
Q - 
Operator
Good afternoon and welcome to the Straight Path Communications’ Fourth Quarter and Year-End Fiscal 2016 Earnings Call and Webcast. All participants will be in a listen-only mode. [Operator Instructions] Please note this event is being recorded.
As a reminder, some of the matters Straight Path management will discuss on this call are forward-looking statements. You should keep in mind that these forward-looking statements are subject to known and unknown risks and uncertainties, and it could cause actual results to differ materially from those expressed or implied by such statements and that such statements are not a guarantee of future performance.
In addition to the factors specifically noted in the forward-looking statements, such risks and uncertainties include, but are not limited to general economic conditions and those factors discussed under the Risk Factors section of our Annual Report on Form 10-K and Quarterly Reports on Form 10-Q and other SEC filings.
The forward-looking statements are made of this date and the Company assumes no obligation to update the forward-looking statements or to update the reasons why actual results could differ from those projected in the forward-looking statements.
Representing Straight Path today are Davidi Jonas, Chief Executive Officer; and Jonathan Rand, Chief Financial Officer. Let me quickly outline the agenda for today's call. Davidi will discuss Straight Path’s achievements and overall strategy. Then, Jonathan will outline the Company's financials and outlook. There will not be an opportunity to ask questions on today's call.
And now, allow me to turn the call over to Straight Path’s CEO, Davidi Jonas. Davidi, the floor is yours.
Davidi Jonas
Thank you and thank you all for joining us on today's call. I would like to discuss some recent developments in our three segments as well as provide some outlook regarding where we are heading. Allow me to begin with Straight Path’s IP Group.
Following our successes at the Federal Circuit Court of Appeals as well as the related hearings at the Patent Trial and Appeals Board, we are now facing an appeal back to the Federal Circuit on the PTAB's conclusions and some of the inter-party reviews challenging the patentability of our patent. Of course, the PTAB's conclusions were informed by the Federal Circuit’s earlier decision, but nonetheless the appellants have appealed as a matter of right.
During the pendency of the appeal, there is a possibility that some or all of our cases pending in Federal District Court will remain or be stayed. The court in the Eastern District of Virginia for instance has elected to keep the stay in place, but the other courts have not yet decided.
In the coming weeks and months, we intend to move forward with attempts at resolution and/or furthering the progress of our cases. Moving on to Straight Path Ventures, our wireless hardware development segment. We recently reported that our Gigabit Mobility Lab conducted a successful indoor demonstration of a development stage prototype 39 GHz 5G [ph] transceiver. The press release describing some of the results as well as a link to a brief video can be found on our website.
The accomplishments of our lab led by our Chief Technology Officer, Jerry Pi exceeded our expectations. In a matter of a few short months and on a relatively small budget, we were able to demonstrate the ability of phased arrays and beamforming with industry standard modulation at 39 GHz. While we still have a lot of work to get to a commercial product, this is an important milestone for our Company.

We are planning an outdoor demonstration in the coming months where we hope to cover a much longer distance and continue to showcase our engineering prowess and the 39 GHz frontier. Of course we hope this raises the profile of not just our technical expertise, but of what can be achieved with 39 GHz. To date much of the industry's millimeter wave testing and demonstrations have been focused at 28 GHz. We hope our efforts will bring greater focus to 39 GHz as well.
Moving on to Straight Path Spectrum. As our press release disclosed following the release of the UMFU Report and Order, the Report and Order released in July adopted rules quite in line with Straight Path’s goals and advocacy. The FCC’s rules include flexible use rates for incumbents, repacking the 39 GHz band, 200 MHz channel sizes; partial economic areas instead of counties unlike at 28 GHz.
Pushing out the next substantial service demonstration to 2024, access to the bands for satellite in a manner that protects terrestrial services, and technical rules that allow for wide area coverage. Aside from the Commission’s rulemaking activity, we are seeing growing adoption of 39 GHz mainly as a result of our investments and efforts.
For example, we recently signed a multiyear lease agreement with a nationwide advanced network communications provider which will serve potentially thousands of customers across dozens of markets using Cambridge Broadband Network’s 39 GHz point-to-multipoint radios and Spectrum lease term out.
At the same time, we have been seeing growing interest in 39 GHz from operators across the country. In anticipation of the availability of 39 GHz PMP, we engaged new lessees to initiate them into 39 GHz. We currently have customers operating on channels covering more than 90% of our licensed holdings by MHz-Pops.
Following the conclusion of our independent investigation, we disclosed the results of the investigation to the FCC and provided additional information requested by the commission. The commission recently sent us a letter of inquiry requesting additional information as part of their investigation. We continue to fully cooperate with the commission.
While we cannot foretell how long the investigation will take nor what the outcome will be, we hope that the investigation will be brought to a satisfactory resolution in a shorter time as is practicable. We will continue to provide updates as developments [warrant].
We continue to be active in the commission's ongoing rulemaking proceeds. We submitted comments to the further notice of proposed rulemaking along with many other industry participants. While we expect the SNPRM to move a bit slower than the initial Report and Order, one can sense the importance that the industry and the commission placed on millimeter wave for the future of wireless communication.
We hope that as the leaders in license millimeter waves, 39 GHz and 28 GHz will set the tone. We have seen a transformation of these bands with the emergence of new technologies and customer demand. We hope to play a vital part in the next generation of fixed and mobile wireless communications.
With that, allow me to turn the call over to our CFO, Jonathan Rand. Jonathan?
Jonathan Rand
Thank you, Davidi. The FCC’s Upper Microwave Flexible Use Report and Order is certainly of a historic nature as the FCC took great steps for the United States to maintain its worldwide competitive stature in wireless communications by making a significant new portion of bandwidth available to support the explosive growth of data consumption via mobile users.
The fact that Straight Path has been in the middle of this process playing a significant role in both the regulatory proceedings and now also via innovative development of next-generation wireless technology testifies to our commitment and vision to make meaningful contributions to the wireless communications industry.

I am pleased to outline our financial results, as we completed the fourth quarter of our fiscal year 2016 and three months ended July 31. I’ll start with the focus on Q4 and then move to a broader look at the entire 2016 fiscal year. For Q4, we recognized revenue of $122,000. This revenue was generated solely by our Spectrum subsidiary and is leveled with Spectrum lease revenue from the previous quarter.
We expect to see Spectrum revenue return to a modest quarterly increase as it had earlier in fiscal 2016. If there is a successful commercial launch and subsequent wireless operator adoption of the Cambridge 39 GHz point-to-multipoint radios expected at the earliest in Q1 of calendar 2017, we would then expect Spectrum lease revenue to increase more rapidly.
Total cost and expenses for the quarter were $4 million consisting of direct cost of revenues, research and development expense, and our SG&A. This compares to $2.1 million in Q3 and $4.2 million one-year ago. We continue to support critical research and development efforts in Q4. We achieved important progress in our Gigabit Mobility Lab and expensed an additional $107,000 towards R&D resulting in our recent 5G 39 GHz transceiver indoor demonstration, a major milestone for our venture segment and team.
In July, Cambridge reached the third of three development milestones towards its 39 GHz point-to-multipoint prototype, so we expensed the final $300,000 against the $1 million prepaid under our development arrangement with Cambridge. This quarters SG&A spend totaled $3.5 million including non-cash compensation of approximately $579,000.
This is up from last quarter's SG&A spending of $1.5 million, primarily due to an increase of expenses regarding our class action litigation and related regulatory matters and the cost of $855,000 for 39 GHz point-to-point equipment deployed via new Spectrum lessees as I will describe further below.
With $122,000 of revenue and $4 million in costs and expenses, we are reporting an operating loss of $3.8 million for Q4. This compares to a $1.8 million operating loss last quarter and $1.4 million operating loss in the year-ago quarter. The loss for this quarter reflects extra spending for SG&A items of equipment, litigation, and regulatory matters.
Moving on to the full fiscal year of 2016, we closed fiscal 2016 with $11.4 million of cash and cash equivalents versus $13.2 million at the end of Q3 and $18.6 million on hand at the close of fiscal year 2015.
Total revenue recognized for fiscal 2016 was $2.2 million versus $13.2 million in the previous year. This drop is due to the reduction in our IP Group's recognized revenue of $1.7 million in this fiscal year versus $12.8 million in fiscal 2015 as we recognized revenue from settlement and licensing arrangements entered into in prior years. This year’s Spectrum revenue of $461,000 increased by 8% over fiscal 2015.
Total cost and expenses for fiscal 2016 were $11.2 million versus $13 million for the previous year. This reduction in total costs and expenses is mainly due to a significant decrease in direct cost of revenue in line with the reduced revenue recognized from our IP settlement offset by increases in SG&A and R&D spending. This year's $11.2 million of expenses breaks out percentage wise approximately as follows; 8.3% direct cost of revenues, 24.6% non-cash compensation, 55.6% SG&A spending excluding the non-cash compensation, and 11.4% towards R&D.
Now I’d like to provide some of the expectations we have for the upcoming quarters. Our operational spending budget for fiscal 2017 is $5.5 million which consist of approximately $1 million per quarter for our general operations, $1 million for the full-year of support for our Gigabit Mobility Lab, and approximately $0.5 million to fund matters related to the shareholder litigation and FCC investigation, although this last component in particular is subject to change depending on future developments. We have also committed to increasing our purchase of CBNL 39 GHz hardware by about $1.3 million as noted last quarter to a total of approximately $2.1 million in total for the year.

On the revenue side, we anticipate there will be an increase in Spectrum lease revenue in fiscal 2017, more likely in the latter half of the year dependent primarily on the CBNL 39 GHz point-to-multipoint hardware being commercialized successfully and in a timely manner. As we previously disclosed in July, we signed a multiyear Spectrum lease agreement with a nationwide advanced network communications provider to lease our 39 GHz Spectrum in dozens of cities for use with CBNL point-to-multipoint radios once they are commercially released.
CBNL is expecting to test working prototypes with several U.S. operators in the coming months. Even if the CBNL radios are ready for commercial deployment, that particular lease should let generate several hundred thousand dollars of Spectrum lease revenue in fiscal 2017 with the expectation to ramp-up significantly. Although, of course, there are various risks inherent to predict future revenue based on new technology and other factors.
It's important to note that this transaction does not sell any Spectrum. As is typical in our Spectrum leasing arrangements, the operator is leasing the Spectrum, while we maintain full ownership of the Spectrum. I wanted to clarify this for our investors as there may have been some confusion related to an announcement released this past July.
Our further consideration regarding revenue, let's look at our IP Group going forward. Our IP Group recorded no revenue in this quarter, and the $96,000 we recorded in Q3 marks the final payment for all settlement and license agreements we have entered into to date. Only in the event that we enter into new settlement and license agreements or sell some or all of the IP will the IP Group generate revenue in the future.
Certainly the fact that we have prevailed in our appeal to the U.S. Court of Appeals and subsequently on remand at the Patent Trial and Appeal Board puts the IP Group in a better position to generate future revenues, although of course that outcome is not certain and there are still significant challenges to meet.
There was one change in our financial statements I'd like to highlight. Regarding our purchase of point-to-point hardware as our investment to increase market adoption of 39 GHz Spectrum in the advance of the availability of Cambridge's system. In fiscal Q3, this was recorded as property and equipment net of depreciation in our balance sheet. For faster adoption and due to the marketing aspect of this campaign, we have reallocated that purchase to a marketing expense, which will be recorded either in SG&A for hardware install or as prepaid marketing expense for all related hardware yet to be installed.
The bottom line regarding our cash balance of a $11.4 million versus our various anticipated operational expenses and possible revenue for fiscal 2017 is that we feel our foreseeably available resources place us in a comfortable position for at least the next 12 months.
I hope this provides you with good insight into our fiscal status and forward-looking vision for Straight Path. There will not be a Q&A session on today's call, so we are ending the call at this time. Davidi and I thank you very much for joining Straight Path Communications’ fourth quarter fiscal 2016 conference call.
Question-and-Answer Session
Operator
 
 
End of Q&A
Operator
This concludes today's conference call. You may now disconnect your lines. Thank you for participating and have a pleasant day.
